Title : Harriet Isabel Ballintine
Text : [[File:Harriet_Ballintine_Portrait_1917.png|thumb|right|A portrait photo of Harriet Ballintine from the 1917 Vassar College yearbook.]]
'''Harriet Isabel Ballintine''' (December 23, 1864 &ndash; February 9, 1951) was the athletic director at [[Vassar College]] from 1891 to 1930 and was a leader in the development of physical education for women.

==Biography==
Harriet Isabel Ballintine was born 23 December 1864 in [[Le Roy, New York]],<ref name="Guide">{{cite web|title=Guide to the Harriet Isabel Ballintine Papers, 1881-1916|url=http://specialcollections.vassar.edu/findingaids/ballintine_harriet.html|publisher=Vassar College Libraries|accessdate=December 5, 2014}}</ref> a small town in Genesee County. She graduated from  [[Ingham University]] in 1888,<ref name="Guide"/> just four years before the institution, sometimes touted as the first University in the United States exclusively for women, was closed due to financial problems.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ingham University, 1837-1892|url=http://www.woodwardmemoriallibrary.org/university.php|accessdate=December 5, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209051336/http://www.woodwardmemoriallibrary.org/university.php|archivedate=December 9, 2014|df=}}</ref> The next year she attended the first class in athletics for women at [[Harvard Summer School]]. After studying in Europe, and graduating from the [[Boston University College of Health and Rehabilitation Sciences (Sargent College)|Sargent School of Physical Training]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], she returned briefly to Ingham as a teacher. She also taught at [[Lasell College|Lasell Seminary]]. In 1891, she moved on to [[Vassar College]] where she was first appointed Director of the Gymnasium, and was later named assistant professor. She taught in the Department of Physical Education until her retirement in 1930.<ref name="Guide"/> Ballintine was responsible for organizing the first collegiate track and field event for women (1895) and also established field hockey not only at Vassar but made it an acceptable sport for women at several institutions in the Northeast.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://newspaperarchives.vassar.edu/cgi-bin/vassar?a=d&d=miscellany19510221-01.2.40&srpos=&dliv=none&e=-------en-20--1--txt-IN-------|title = Vassar Miscellany News|date = 21 February 1951|accessdate = 10 June 2014|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

Ballintine served as an instructor at the [[Harvard Summer School]] in 1901 and 1902.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Vassarian, 1917, page 39|url=https://archive.org/stream/vassarion00vass#page/n41/mode/2up/search/Ballantine|publisher=Vassar College|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref> It was there in 1901 that she met [[Constance Applebee]] and invited the Englishwoman to demonstrate field hockey at Vassar.<ref name="britannica">{{cite web|title=Constance M. K. Applebee|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/30655/Constance-MK-Applebee|publisher=Encyclop√¶dia Britannica|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref> Later that year, Ballintine and Applebee helped to found the American Field Hockey Association, which governed the sport in the United States for 20 years.<ref name="britannica"/>

In 1933, the trustees of Vassar College named the campus hockey field and the adjoining road Ballintine Field and Ballintine Road, respectively, after her.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://newspaperarchives.vassar.edu/cgi-bin/vassar?a=d&d=miscellany19330930-01.2.19&srpos=&dliv=none&e=-------en-20--1--txt-IN-------|title = Vassar Miscellany News|date = 30 September 1933|accessdate = 5 December 2014|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

